\begin_layout Standard
What is the detuning in terms in the Hamiltonian case? We have a laser of
 frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 interacting with a cavity that has a resonant frequency given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 This is similar to the setup of a field interacting with an atom that has
 a resonant frequency given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, and where the detuning is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}-\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 So it is reasonable to postulate that the detuning is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}-\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us try to clearly establish this statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A cavity has resonant modes given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{m}=2\pi m\Delta\nu,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu\equiv c/2nd$
\end_inset

 is the free-spectral-range (eq:defFreeSpectralRange), where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the length of the Fabry-perot cavity.
 In the Hamiltonian approach, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to 1.
 We expect that only a mode interacts with the laser and it is the mode
 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{m}\left|\omega_{m}-\omega_{0}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

 is the frequency that can is the solution of this optimization procedure.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{c}=2\pi l\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

 for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the detuned Fabry-Perot case we had that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}\tau=\theta+n\pi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta=\frac{\theta}{\tau}=\omega_{0}-\frac{n\pi}{\tau}=\omega_{0}-\frac{n\pi c}{L}=\omega_{0}-2\frac{n\pi c}{2L}=\omega_{0}-\omega_{c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\pi c/L=2n\pi\left(c/2L\right)$
\end_inset

 is just the cavity resonant frequency that is closest to the laser frequency.
 Thus, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}-\omega_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 So from now on, we will call this quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

