According to the two-photon formalism, in the narrow sideband limit, one
 moves from an operator in the cosine/sine quadrature picture, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \gamma_{c},\gamma_{s}\right\} $
\end_inset

 to a complex amplitude quadrature operator, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ d,d^{\dagger}\right\} $
\end_inset

, via (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:sidesbands2photonAcAs"

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\gamma_{c}\left(\Omega\right)=\frac{d\left(\omega+\Omega\right)+d^{\dagger}\left(\omega-\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\gamma_{s}\left(\Omega\right)=\frac{d\left(\omega+\Omega\right)-d^{\dagger}\left(\omega-\Omega\right)}{i\sqrt{2}}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the central frequency of the laser.
 We can then also write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{c}\left(\Omega\right)-i\gamma_{s}\left(\Omega\right)=\frac{2}{\sqrt{2}}d^{\dagger}\left(\omega-\Omega\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{d^{\dagger}\left(\omega-\Omega\right)=\frac{\gamma_{c}\left(\Omega\right)-i\gamma_{s}\left(\Omega\right)}{\sqrt{2}}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


